The triumph of the right-wing populists in Austria: 29% of the total
The perceptible weakening of both parties in the grand coalition and the marked strengthening of the right-wing populist parties led, according to preliminary results, to early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), in which the position of the current President, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously wavering, has suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the contrary, the elected leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Kärnten sub-prefect Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to national politics.
According to the provisional results, the strongest party in the country is still the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8% of the votes, but it lost 5.5% compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which lost almost 9% of the vote with 25.6%.
These are the worst results of these two great parties in the postwar Austrian history and above all the literally catastrophic result of the Volks, which provoked early elections.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the Volkspartei had a considerable advantage in preferences over the SPÖ.
But the voters have obviously punished them for bringing down the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman, Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Monterer.
Observers believe it could happen as early as Monday during the extraordinary party leadership meeting.
This development should perhaps facilitate the path towards the increasingly likely exit from the election result, i.e. towards the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
The Social Democrats, however, were concerned about the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the FPÖ gained 18% and the BZÖ 11% of the vote - but the Social Democrats also expressed concern about another year, 1999, when the populists joined the popular parties in the collective government (the FPÖ was still united, but in 2005 it split from the BZÖ), which was even the reason for sanctions by the European Union.
This is clearly the case for Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party and presumes a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Greens also entered Parliament, but fell slightly, dropping from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has clearly passed the 4% threshold and not entered Parliament.
