Promoters are seeing increasing numbers of bookings
It looks like it's going to be a good winter for German tour operators:
One study shows that the turnover of travel bookings for the coming months compared to the previous year has increased significantly - for the winter season even by more than 30%.
Despite weak economic prospects, the desire to travel among Germans remains strong, according to a survey.
The German tourism association DRV reported on Monday that bookings for the winter season had seen a 31% increase in turnover compared with the same period last year.
According to the survey of the market research institute GfK, there are already increased booking quotas for the autumn months.
The surplus of travel agencies for October compared with 2007 would therefore amount to approximately 11%, the DRV informed.
The basis for these results are the figures from GfK, which analyses the booking data of 1200 German travel agencies on a monthly basis and produces statistical projections for the entire market.
It would also include travel bookings made up to the end of August 2008.
Due to the weakening of the dollar, travel to the United States would be particularly in demand, DRV reported.
The increase in bookings would be about one third.
The German people would also be particularly interested in Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as in Germany.
The price of all-inclusive travel is particularly high, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
Given the rising costs of energy and foodstuffs, the costs would be better calculated for customers than for an individually organised holiday.
Consumers could save money through, among other things, discounts on bookings made well in advance or all-inclusive deals, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also reported to have been very good, with a surplus of bookings again compared to the previous year - although according to a further study the number of Germans who had travelled was down on the previous year.
