Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were anxious to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 paces into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands astride the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking out over the world like some German provincial town halls.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling to the vault, there is no doubt as to the grandeur of the undertaking of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions of dominating the Middle East by means of this railway that ran from Damascus, to Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions were dashed by World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The isolation of the region from the surrounding region, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has been overcome by the
British and Dominion forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for the Hyderpasha station too.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded, destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has been slowly falling into disrepair, largely overtaken by history.
But today, this railway junction to Anatolia and all points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight the ever-larger diplomatic horizons of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the ice-boundary of the Cold War, is over.
There's a new engagement policy now.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy run down the slopes that produced the old-world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has suggested some suspects in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, a state-of-the-art stone and steel facility - built on purpose - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-sized shopping malls and power bakeries, where business suit managers - both men and women - meet to do deals early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Full suit, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its nearest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today, you must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't one or the other.
It has to be both.
"But surely at some point", I ask, "Turkey will be forced to decide?"
"Turkey", he says, "does not want to face that choice".
He then makes a point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has recited from memory: that the links of the Middle East, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically ride those rail lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another sleepless night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions may now be, in large part, in the hands of Turkey.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called the "sick man of Europe".
At least then there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent should lay claim to this fascinating land.
