The "bee car" to avoid collisions
In developing technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has drawn inspiration from nature, and in particular from bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking the flight of bees as an example, can avoid accidents.
It's the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision-avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technology Center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general director of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the four-area Safety Shield produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer's vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to the safety shield of the Nissan.
But the most important thing is the bees' compound eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly uninterruptedly into its own space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers have developed what they call a laser range finder.
This mechanism detects obstacles in front of the BR23C within a radius of two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately allows to prevent the collision.
"Once it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning its wheels at a right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it were not so, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and chief engineer on this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction its wheels can turn and not by exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the little robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and to act on this data.
It does not require the memorization of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can run without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes".
It's the first step in developing new technologies for instant collision avoidance, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination by avoiding obstacles along the way.
