Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced that it had signed an agreement with Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, to invest nine billion dollars in a 21% stake in the company, following a sharp fall in its shares on the stock market.
A week after the drafting of a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's stock at a cost of $25.25 each, or a sum equivalent to $3 billion.
The price set is 19% below the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will also invest USD 6 billion in the purchase of convertible bonds at a conversion price of USD 31,25 with a 10% yield.
Morgan Stanley said that the global transaction would be carried out on the basis of an average price of USD 29 per share, or 28% below its current price.
However, by 5 p.m., the Morgan Stanley stock was down 6.79% to $23.07.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to a bank holding company", explained John Mack, the American group's managing director.
