Benelux governments to nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries have helped the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to fall into difficulties as a result of the crisis in the American credit market, by partially nationalising it. The three countries will provide 11.2 billion euro to the financial and insurance institution, with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands reached an agreement at the highest level over the weekend, involving the president of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for competition.
The first major crisis in the eurozone in the context of the difficulties which have been affecting the international financial market for more than a year was the one affecting Fortis Bank, and in a certain sense the decisions taken in this regard can be seen as setting a precedent.
The decision taken on Sunday night means that all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's shares in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first of all the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' shares started with a vertical collapse, and the second half of the week saw the institution's serious signs of crisis.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to fail.
The bank's stock fell nearly 12 percent on Friday, the lowest in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
The total capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion at current share prices, but according to the bank's management this is not real.
The summit blamed the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the extra-European market due to the acceptance of the US plan of 700 billion dollars.
On Monday the headline slowly began to rise again.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy bid.
The Belgian Government had previously assured investors that they should not fear losing their money.
The bank's customers were not panicked, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches and has also acquired leasing companies.
The Fox in the Chicken House
Life and health insurers in America, based on people's purchase of medication data, often refuse to take out an insurance policy.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become unmanageable.
'There is a privacy programme under which the use of prescription data for medicines is in any case subject to the consent of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like handing the chicken to the fox", writes the Washington Post, quoting Richard Dick, author of the program to follow prescriptions.
Insurance companies base the insurance premium and the amount of compensation due in the event of an accident on the state of health of the potential customer and do not insure if they consider the risk too high.
In the past, the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper process 10 years ago: based on the customer's ID code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines you have bought in the last year and a half and from this the program can tell you what diseases you suffer from and what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol lowering drugs, this means that the level of fat in your blood is practically unhealthily high and is classified in the higher risk category.
There are various versions of the programme on the market, some of which also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not have much left over, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the contraindications is that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are used against migraine or hot flashes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance and commercial policy, is a risk-increasing factor, the first two are not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have not yet imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies are also now processing lab test results and linking them to medication consumption data to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it will be increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate privacy law but it only applies to health care and insurance.
There's a bill before Congress that gives the authorities the power to regulate data-driven companies.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: that is why he has developed a program that links the forwarding of data with the consent expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot deny the approval because otherwise the insurers do not stipulate the contract.
So in the end the hens are left to the mercy of the fox.
